Understanding Trace Performance
When analyzing your traces, look for typical timing patterns: Amazon API Gateway responses should be under 100ms, Amazon EventBridge routing adds 10-20ms overhead, and AWS Lambda handlers typically execute in 100-500ms. Background processors may take 1-5 seconds for complex operations like payment authorization.

Focus on span duration to identify slow operations, examine metadata to understand which specific resources are involved, and trace request IDs to follow individual orders through the system. Error details in failed spans show exact failure points, while parent-child relationships reveal your processing flow.

Your event-driven architecture creates both sequential flows (Amazon API Gateway → Amazon EventBridge → AWS Lambda) that must happen in order, and parallel processing (multiple Amazon SQS processors) that can run simultaneously. Long spans often indicate bottlenecks in Amazon DynamoDB queries or AWS Lambda cold starts (when functions haven't been invoked recently and need to initialize).

