Service Dependencies
Your system has clear dependency patterns: Amazon API Gateway serves as the entry point with no dependencies, but its failure makes the entire system unavailable. Cart operations depend only on Amazon DynamoDB, while checkout operations require both Amazon EventBridge and Amazon DynamoDB. Amazon EventBridge failures stop all async processing, Amazon SQS issues cause processing delays, and Amazon DynamoDB problems affect data operations across the system.

Understanding these dependencies helps you prioritize monitoring and design resilience strategies. Critical path components like Amazon API Gateway and Amazon DynamoDB require the highest availability, while individual processor failures only affect specific order steps.

Lab 5.6: AWS Lambda Performance Optimization Insights
Performance Optimization
Common performance issues include AWS Lambda cold start delays when functions haven't been invoked recently (address with provisioned concurrency for predictable performance, though this changes the serverless cost model from pure pay-per-use to reserved capacity), database latency from inefficient Amazon DynamoDB queries (optimize partition keys and use Amazon DynamoDB's automatic scaling capabilities), queue processing delays (AWS Lambda automatically scales concurrency based on Amazon SQS queue depth, but you can adjust reserved concurrency limits), and complex Amazon EventBridge rules (simplify patterns to reduce event routing overhead).

Monitor key metrics: Amazon API Gateway response times should stay under 200ms (investigate if over 500ms - Amazon API Gateway automatically scales but may throttle under extreme load), AWS Lambda duration under 1000ms (optimize if over 3000ms - longer execution times increase costs in the pay-per-use model), Amazon DynamoDB latency under 50ms (review queries if over 100ms - Amazon DynamoDB auto-scales read/write capacity but inefficient queries still impact performance), and queue processing under 30 seconds (AWS Lambda processors scale automatically based on queue depth, but complex processing may require timeout adjustments).

Serverless Cost Optimization: In serverless architectures, performance directly impacts cost. Faster AWS Lambda functions consume fewer compute resources and cost less per execution. Efficient Amazon DynamoDB queries reduce read/write capacity consumption. Optimized Amazon EventBridge rules reduce event processing overhead. The pay-per-use model means performance improvements translate directly to cost savings.

